n the 1960s and 1970s, which paved the way for national assaults on welfare. Taking a fresh look at recent debates on welfare reform, she explores how and why politicians competing for the white vote and right-wing think tanks promoting business interests appeased the Christian right and manufactured consent for cutbacks through a powerful, racially coded discourse. Finally, through firsthand testimonies, Reese vividly portrays the tragic consequences of current welfare policies and calls for a bold new agenda for working families.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Mai 2022) 0aAid to families with dependent children programs. 0aPublic welfarexHistoryxUnited States. 0aPublic welfarezUnited StatesxHistory. 0aSingle mothersxGovernment policyxUnited States. 0aSingle mothersxGovernment policyzUnited States. 0aWelfare recipientsxEmploymentxUnited States. 0aWelfare recipientsxEmploymentzUnited States. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Sociology / General.2bisacsh  a1940s.  a20th century.  aafrican americans.  aamerica.  aamerican society.  aamerican welfare.  aantiwelfare campaigns.  ablack americans.  achicanos.  acontemporary america.  ademographic studies.  aethnographers.  aethnography.  ahistorical perspective.  alow income families.  amotherhood.  amothers.  anonfiction.  aparenting.  apolitical history.  apoliticians.  apuerto ricans.  aracism.  asafety net.  awelfare culture.  awelfare history.  awelfare opposition.  awelfare policies.  awelfare system.  aworking class families.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013z978311069042240uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052093871740uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520938717423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520938717/orig